Done. I implemented the enforcement path.

What changed:

- `popdam3`: removed `supabase db push` from the deploy workflow and deleted the `EXTERNAL_SUPABASE_DB_PASSWORD` GitHub secret.
- `popdam3`, `popcrm-web`, `poppim-web`, `directus`: added `Forbid Shared DB Bypass` CI workflow to block app-owned `supabase/migrations/*.sql` changes and DB mutation commands in changed automation files.
- `shared-db`: added the official serialized migration workflow, with preview/production dry-run/apply as manual actions only.
- `shared-db`: added the migration-capable GitHub secrets there only:
  - `SUPABASE_ACCESS_TOKEN`
  - `SUPABASE_DB_PASSWORD_PREVIEW`
  - `SUPABASE_DB_PASSWORD_PRODUCTION`
- Opened and merged shared-db PR #31.
- Confirmed all new app guard workflows passed, and app deploy workflows completed successfully.

One limitation: GitHub rejected push rulesets because these repos are public/user-owned in a way that does not support push rules. So the hard enforcement is now: app repos do not have the DB password, app workflows no longer run migrations, and CI blocks future attempts to add migration files or migration commands.

Commits pushed:

- `popdam3`: `9069ed1`
- `popcrm-web`: `83f10f2`
- `poppim-web`: `f10997c`
- `directus`: `268511d`
- `shared-db`: merged PR #31 to `main`

